Now, we load our dataset and let us check what happens when you turn your data into time series. Since our data is repeated every 3 months we have to use 4 as a parameter for the frequency:

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
df <- read.xlsx(('data_g6.xlsx'),sheetIndex=1)
names(df) <- c('Fecha','Esfuerzo')
plot(df, main="Adjusted Closing Prices", col="blue")
df.ts <- ts(df[,2], frequency=4, start=c(1995,1))
plot(df.ts, main="Adjusted Closing Prices", col="blue")

STATIONARITY OF THE DATA?

We can observe from the previous plot that we do not have a clear trend neither a seasonal component. The series do not look like as stationary but we need to be sure about it in order to make further assumptions. Stationarity means that the mean, variance and autocorrelation structure of a time series do not change over time. We will now use the decompose method in order to see a more detailed description of the topics discussed:

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
decomp.df <- decompose(df.ts)
#decomp.df
plot(decomp.df)

Sometimes we can do some transformations to minimize this effects in case we have a multiplicative decomposition where the seasonal efect is higher as the trend increases. We can apply logarithmic or Box-Cox transformations, but in our case we can see that it is not worth it:

plot(log(df.ts), main="Adjusted Closing Prices", col="blue")

In order to check the maths of the lack of stationarity we can group our data by year and calculate the mean values and the variance.

df$year <- substr(df$Fecha,1,4)
df2 <- ddply(df,~year,summarise,mean=mean(Esfuerzo),vari=var(Esfuerzo),vari2 = var(log(Esfuerzo)))
df2.ts <- ts(df2[,c(2,3,4)], frequency=1, start=c(1995))
plot(df2.ts, main="Mean & Variance Over the Years", col="blue")

Now, it is more clear that both the mean and the variance change over time and that we do not get any possitive effect from using the log transformation.

DECOMPOSING AND FORECASTING WITH STL.

Now, we are using another decomposing method similar to the one we used before, splitting the series into seasonal, trend and irregular components:

stl1.df <- stl(df.ts,s.window="periodic",  robust = TRUE)
plot(stl1.df)

We can do an initial forecast by 2 different methods with our time series already decompossed:

#forecasting with stl()
fcst=forecast(stl1.df, method="naive")
plot(fcst)

So, we are facing a problem of additive series since the log transformation did not make any improvement on the variance effects. Let us study now the remainder part and see if it looks like white noise (mean zero and no correlation between its values at different times).

df2.stl.remainder <- stl1.df$time.series[,c("remainder")]
tsdisplay(df2.stl.remainder)

Residuals would look like a white noise if we deal with the high crests that may seem as outliers. We have some correlation on the residuals. Let’s see if we can solve this issue by fitting an Arima model.

ARIMA MODEL

For fitting our arima model, we have to decide firstly if we are using our original data or the logarithmic of it. We have already seen that using the log transformation does not make any improvement, so the simpler, the better:

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
plot(log(df.ts), main="Adjusted Closing Prices", col="blue")
plot(df.ts, main="Adjusted Closing Prices", col="blue")

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

After that we have to think about if we have to consider a seasonal component.

ggmonthplot(df.ts)

ggseasonplot(df.ts)

#tsdisplay(log(df.ts), plot.type = "spectrum")
# par(mfrow=c(1,2))
# seasonplot((df.ts))
# monthplot((df.ts))

Seasonplot and monthplot are comented since they are quite similar to the ggplots graphs but they look less nice. From these we can infer that there is not a clear seasonal component since the mean remains constant over the years. Now, we need to make our timeseries stationary and we are using diff method to do so. We have to decide now how many times do we need to diff in order to achieve that seasonarity. There are some automatics methods such as ndiffs() but we will trust the least we are able in automatized methods and we are trying to figure it out by ourselves.

tsdisplay(diff((df.ts)))

tsdisplay(diff((df.ts), differences = 2))

c('TSERIES',var(df.ts),'DIFF-',var(diff(df.ts)),'2DIFF',var(diff(diff(df.ts))))
## [1] "TSERIES"          "32.448754165124"  "DIFF-"           
## [4] "2.63045281582953" "2DIFF"            "3.54197183098592"

We can see that the first graph looks more flat thant the second one, and we confirm it by printing out the values of the variance of the original time series and the first and second differenced tseries, since the variance of the second diff is greater than the first one.

Once we know the d parameter of our Arima model (d = 1), we have to search for p and q. We can do this by looking at the acf2 plots:

tserie = diff(df.ts)

We will look just athe first spikes of our plot. This is quite opened to personal interpretations. Since we can see kind of exponential decay of the ACF plot after the first spike we are going to try with a (p,d,q) = (1,1,0) model and see what do we get. Other way to do it is trying little by little to adjust all the parameters by try and failure. Remember that we have declined the possible existence of a seasonal component:

df_ari1 = Arima(df.ts, order=c(1,1,0))

Our residuals are similar to a white noise series (random serie) if we omit the outliers. By looking at the graphs, we observe that our residuals follow a normal distribution and the autocorrelation and the partial autocorrelation are low. These conclusions are supported by statisticals test:

jarque.bera.test(df_ari1$residuals)
## 
##  Jarque Bera Test
## 
## data:  df_ari1$residuals
## X-squared = 209.72, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16
Box.test(df_ari1$residuals, lag=12)
## 
##  Box-Pierce test
## 
## data:  df_ari1$residuals
## X-squared = 4.4573, df = 12, p-value = 0.9737

The p-value of the box.test and the one we obtained in the ljung-box test do no reject the null hypothesis of independence of our residuals and the jarque bera result suggests that our distribution is not normal, which may be caused by the 4-6 outliers we can see in the plot of the model fitted.

tsdiag(df_ari1)

MODEL CHOICE

Both 3 models are similar in terms of its statistical properties, their plotting look similar too with kind of white noise appearance despite the outliers. They all show uncorrelated residuals (with similar patterns) and without making a study of the outliers they do not show normality (on the jarque bera test). The third model is the only one that includes a seasonal component and since it is the one with the lower AICc value and the one that has best values on its metrics I would choose that one, despite the fact that it has been recommended by a function and being the hardest one because of its seasonal component. Now, we just have to forecast with the model choosen.

FORECAST

Since we have already discovered there might be an additive season component on our data we can do some forecast with ets model and with the “arima way”.

plot(forecast(df_ari3))

df_ets = ets(df.ts, model = "AAA")
df_ets_f=forecast(df_ets,h=24)
plot(df_ets_f)

We can see that the grey? margins are bigger as the time goes by, which is a logical consequence from the increase of the uncertainty. From our point of view, the one that that seems more likely to happen is the first one since it introduces a kind of moody trend which is consequent with our true data. The ets model forecast a rather flat timeseries which may be perhaps a little bit unreal. But we are not sorcerers with powers to guess the future!!

Another utility we get for this is possibility of retrieving the exact value predicted from the model with a given certainty and we can see that they are consequent with the plots we got.
